<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-638-717  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 638 717.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Lasers andamp; Optronics  Nov 1990 v9 n11 p51(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>New fiberoptic paths for surgical lasers; silica-core fibersenhance performance of medical laser delivery systems.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>McCann, Brian P.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Flexible laster-beam delivery systems are an important part oflaser surgery.andP;  Advances in laser technology result ingeneral-surgery laser systems that give the surgeon one tool tocut and vaporize tissue and coagulate blood vessels.andP;  The primarycomponent in medical laser delivery systems is the optical fiber.andO;There are three main types of silica-core optical fibers inmedical laser delivery systems: plastica-clad silica fiber,hard-fluoropolymer-clad fiber, and glass-clad fiber.andP;  Otheradvances include contact-tip delivery systems that concentrate thelaser energy to a small point on the tip; sapphire tips, used as afree-beam or contact system; tapered fibers, a one-piece contactsurgery tool to cut and coagulate; and all-silica fiber, usedmainly in applications that need high power stability, very lowbeam divergence, or deep-ultraviolet transmission.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     LasersFiber OpticsMedicineSurgery.andO;Feature:   illustrationcharttable.andO;Caption:   Typical spectral response curves for high-OH and low-OH silicafibers. (chart)A variety of silica-core fibers. (chart)A comparison of silica-core fibers. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>